post_text: Aberdeen Schools: Good Morning, As we prepare for the 20-21 school year, we wanted to reach out to our parents. If you are not comfortable sending your children to school due to the current environment, we certainly respect that. We will offer a virtual/distance option. We had some questions about the difference between this and homeschooling. The virtual/distance option would require you to enroll your student and your student would receive, to the best of our ability, the same services as students attending in the hybrid model. They would receive our curriculum and we would have a staff member that would be assigned to them to offer assistance. We look forward to what appears to be the "new normal" as we continue preparations for 20-21 school year. Thank you.
text: Aberdeen Schools: Good Morning, As we prepare for the 20-21 school year, we wanted to reach out to our parents. If you are not comfortable sending your children to school due to the current environment, we certainly respect that. We will offer a virtual/distance option. We had some questions about the difference between this and homeschooling. The virtual/distance option would require you to enroll your student and your student would receive, to the best of our ability, the same services as students attending in the hybrid model. They would receive our curriculum and we would have a staff member that would be assigned to them to offer assistance. We look forward to what appears to be the "new normal" as we continue preparations for 20-21 school year. Thank you.

shared_text:
Belle Shivers Middle School
March 30 at 9:27 PM ·

Message from Superintendent Jeff Clay...

Good evening and sorry for the late message. With a confirmed case of COVID-19 in our community, the school district feels, for the safety of our students, staff, and community, it is the best decision to temporarily suspend our feeding program. While we understand this is an inconvenience for some stakeholders, we feel this is the most appropriate decision in these very unstable times. Thank you for your understanding, as we gather more information, we will do our best to effectively communicate with all stakeholders when it is safe to re-start the feeding program. Our thoughts go out to the entire community and please stay safe and please do your part to flatten the curve.

We appreciate your patience as we work to provide support through this extended school closure.

C Spire will provide K-12 students in Mississippi public schools with free access to dozens of online learning websites so they can continue their studies from home during this time, it was announced Thursday.
The company’s decision means students’ access on these approved websites using a C Spire wireless device will not count against the data use in their plan.
C Spire worked with sources that surveyed most of the state’s 151 school districts to identify, develop and test the approved learning websites for mobile broadband internet accessibility. The list features some of the most popular and widely available K-12 online learning sites in public education circles. For more information about C Spire’s response to the COVID-19 public health emergency, go to C Spire Cares. To view
the list and receive updates of approved online websites for free wireless data
